Hi Andrew,
Sorry for late to answer your question.
Due to I trace more detail in kernel then hope can answer it correctly.
When issuing "reboot" command on BMC that will call reboot syscall as below.

kernel/reboot.c:
SYSCALL_DEFINE4(reboot)
->case LINUX_REBOOT_CMD_RESTART:
  ->kernel_restart(NULL);
    ->machine_restart()
      ->do_kernel_restart()
        ->atomic_notifier_call_chain(&restart_handler_list, reboot_mode, cmd)

drivers/watchdog/watchdog_core.c:
xxx_wdt_probe() (xxx platform wdt driver)
->devm_watchdog_register_device()
  ->watchdog_register_device()
    ->__watchdog_register_device()
      ->if (wdd->ops->restart) {
            wdd->restart_nb.notifier_call = watchdog_restart_notifier;
            ret = register_restart_handler(&wdd->restart_nb);
        }

If your platform had implement your own watchdog driver,
and watchdog_restart_notifier() will be called with register_restart_handler().
Eventually, your own watchdog reset ops will executed.
Thus, the "reboot" command will involve watchdog reset mechanism to achieve it.

BTW, according linux watchdog framework, we can use WDIOC_GETBOOTSTATUS
to get boot status if your platform have implement watchdog driver
to monitor status of the watchdog device at boot.
That's why we leverage linux watchdog to implement this feature on BMC.

Sincerely,
Tim

Patch Set 13:

Hi Thang Q. Nguyen,

This CONFIG_WATCHDOG_SYSFS kernel config is use to enable linux watchdog sysfs
support. According linux watchdog framework, you need write watchdog driver to
support bootstatus information for your platform.

In watchdog driver, you can check SCU_SYS_EXT_RESET_FLAG or related registers
to update wdt->wdd.bootstatus then /sys/class/watchdog/watchdog0/bootstatus
should show the reset cause information as your expectation.

Sincerely,
Tim

Thang, I think it is worth pointing out that Tim is mostly focused on Nuvoton systems and the driver on Nuvoton systems already supports this flag.  The Aspeed one does not, but when this feature was added, it was hopefully done in a way that once the Aspeed driver adds support the rest of the code will automatically follow.

If you want this support but do not want to make the driver changes yourself, I suggest pointing this feature out to your development contacts at Aspeed.
